                      "description":  "\u003cp\u003eThe relationship between race, genetics, and IQ is one of the most politically sensitive areas in science, which means it\u0027s also one of the most poorly understood. This book examines what the peer-reviewed research actually says, without the ideological filtering that usually shapes how these findings get reported.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou\u0027ll work through the history of intelligence research, the genetic and environmental factors that influence IQ scores, the documented group differences in test results and what scientists currently believe explains them, the methodological debates within the research community, and the political history of how this science has been both weaponized and suppressed depending on who is in power.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat you gain is the ability to engage with this evidence honestly, understanding both what it shows and what its limits are. The goal is clarity, not a predetermined conclusion. Informed people can handle complicated facts.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you want to understand what the science actually says rather than what you\u0027ve been told it says, this book is the place to start.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch6\u003e\u003cspan\u003eProduct Details\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/h6\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eDimensions: \u003cstrong\u003e6 ΟÉβÄî 9 inches / 15.24 x 22.86 cm\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCover: \u003cstrong\u003ePaperback\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e",
